{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775863566002,"sessionID":"ses_28648f112ffezeBig0vH7hGGOs","part":{"id":"prt_d79b7849b0014rlwATd4IX7CqB","messageID":"msg_d79b77576001MAkq29V9WgCSOj","sessionID":"ses_28648f112ffezeBig0vH7hGGOs","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_6453a736473b4a82a6532a40","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: This proposal implements the PicoD command execution API for the `pkg/picod` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n6: \n7: 1. **Secure Command Execution** - Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments with proper isolation\n8: 2. **Resource Limit Enforcement** - Enforce CPU, memory, time, and output size limits on command execution\n9: 3. **Output Capture and Streaming** - Capture stdout/stderr with optional streaming for long-running commands\n10: 4. **Cancellation Support** - Enable command cancellation via context for graceful termination\n11: 5. **Security Hardening** - Implement security validations to prevent privilege escalation and command injection\n12: \n13: This implementation builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in AR-012 and provides the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n14: \n15: ## Scope\n16: \n17: **Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n18: **Language:** Go  \n19: **Size:** M\n20: \n21: This AR covers:\n22: \n23: - **In scope:**\n24:   - Core `PicoD` struct and initialization (`picod.go`)\n25:   - Command execution logic with resource limits (`executor.go`)\n26:   - Resource limit configuration and enforcement (`limits.go`)\n27:   - Output capture and streaming (`output.go`)\n28:   - Security validations and sandboxing (`security.go`)\n29:   - Unit tests with mocked executors\n30:   - Integration tests with real command execution\n31:   - Configuration via environment variables\n32: \n33: - **Out of scope:**\n34:   - Container runtime integration (covered in AR-005, AR-009)\n35:   - Network namespace manipulation\n36:   - User namespace management\n37:   - Filesystem isolation beyond chroot/workspace jail\n38:   - Distributed command execution\n39:   - PicoD HTTP daemon (covered in `code-execution/` specs)\n40: \n41: ## Current State Analysis\n42: \n43: ### Existing Sandbox Infrastructure\n44: \n45: The current system has sandbox management infrastructure:\n46: \n47: 1. **Sandbox Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox/`):\n48:    - Creates and manages sandbox pods\n49:    - Handles lifecycle (create, update, delete)\n50:    - Supports warm pool for pre-provisioned sandboxes\n51: \n52: 2. **CodeInterpreter CRD** (`pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1/types.go`):\n53:    - Defines `CodeInterpreterSpec` with image, command, args, env, resources\n54:    - Supports `AuthMode` enum (`picod` or `none`)\n55:    - Default image: `volcanosh/picod:latest`\n56: \n57: 3. **Workload Manager**:\n58:    - Handles `CodeInterpreter` resources\n59:    - Creates underlying sandbox pods\n60:    - Injects `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` when `AuthMode=picod`\n61: \n62: ### Gaps Identified\n63: \n64: 1. **No unified execution API** - Command execution logic is scattered or non-existent\n65: 2. **No resource limit enforcement** - No programmatic way to enforce CPU/memory/time limits\n66: 3. **No output streaming** - Cannot stream output for long-running commands\n67: 4. **No security hardening** - Missing input validation and sandboxing at the API level\n68: 5. **No cancellation support** - Cannot gracefully cancel running commands\n69: \n70: ### PicoD Context\n71: \n72: Per `code-execution/design.md` and `code-execution/spec.md`:\n73: - PicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail\n74: - Exposes health endpoint with JWT (RSA)-protected APIs\n75: - CLI flags: `-port` (default 8080), `-workspace` (default: current working directory)\n76: - Server uses `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds\n77: \n78: ## Proposed Changes\n79: \n80: ### 1. Core PicoD Structure (`picod.go`)\n81: \n82: ```go\n83: // PicoD represents a command execution sandbox\n84: type PicoD struct {\n85:     sandboxID    string\n86:     workDir      string\n87:     limits       *ResourceLimits\n88:     securityOpts *SecurityOptions\n89:     logger       klog.Logger\n90: }\n91: \n92: // Option is a functional option for PicoD\n93: type Option func(*PicoD)\n94: \n95: // New creates a new PicoD instance\n96: func New(sandboxID string, opts ...Option) *PicoD\n97: \n98: // WithWorkDir sets the working directory\n99: func WithWorkDir(dir string) Option\n100: \n101: // WithLimits sets resource limits\n102: func WithLimits(limits *ResourceLimits) Option\n103: \n104: // WithSecurityOpts sets security options\n105: func WithSecurityOpts(opts *SecurityOptions) Option\n106: \n107: // WithLogger sets the logger\n108: func WithLogger(logger klog.Logger) Option\n109: ```\n110: \n111: ### 2. Resource Limits (`limits.go`)\n112: \n113: ```go\n114: // ResourceLimits defines execution resource limits\n115: type ResourceLimits struct {\n116:     // Timeout is the maximum execution duration\n117:     Timeout time.Duration\n118:     \n119:     // MaxCPU is the maximum CPU cores (e.g., 0.5, 1.0)\n120:     MaxCPU float64\n121:     \n122:     // MaxMemory is the maximum memory in bytes\n123:     MaxMemory int64\n124:     \n125:     // MaxOutputSize is the maximum output size in bytes\n126:     MaxOutputSize int64\n127:     \n128:     // MaxProcesses is the maximum number of processes\n129:     MaxProcesses int\n130: }\n131: \n132: // DefaultResourceLimits returns default resource limits\n133: func DefaultResourceLimits() *ResourceLimits\n134: \n135: // Validate validates resource limits\n136: func (l *ResourceLimits) Validate() error\n137: ```\n138: \n139: ### 3. Security Options (`security.go`)\n140: \n141: ```go\n142: // SecurityOptions defines security settings for command execution\n143: type SecurityOptions struct {\n144:     // UID is the user ID to run commands as\n145:     UID int\n146:     \n147:     // GID is the group ID to run commands as\n148:     GID int\n149:     \n150:     // Capabilities is the list of allowed capabilities\n151:     Capabilities []string\n152:     \n153:     // ReadOnlyFS makes the filesystem read-only\n154:     ReadOnlyFS bool\n155:     \n156:     // NoNetwork disables network access\n157:     NoNetwork bool\n158:     \n159:     // AllowedCommands is an optional allowlist of command paths\n160:     AllowedCommands []string\n161: }\n162: \n163: // DefaultSecurityOpts returns default security options\n164: func DefaultSecurityOpts() *SecurityOptions\n165: \n166: // Validate validates security options\n167: func (o *SecurityOptions) Validate() error\n168: ```\n169: \n170: ### 4. Command Execution API (`executor.go`)\n171: \n172: ```go\n173: // Command represents a command to execute\n174: type Command struct {\n175:     // Path is the command path\n176:     Path string\n177:     \n178:     // Args are the command arguments\n179:     Args []string\n180:     \n181:     // Env is the environment variables\n182:     Env []string\n183:     \n184:     // Dir is the working directory\n185:     Dir string\n186:     \n187:     // Stdin is the standard input\n188:     Stdin io.Reader\n189:     \n190:     // Stdout is the standard output (optional, captured if nil)\n191:     Stdout io.Writer\n192:     \n193:     // Stderr is the standard error (optional, captured if nil)\n194:     Stderr io.Writer\n195: }\n196: \n197: // CommandResult represents the result of command execution\n198: type CommandResult struct {\n199:     // ExitCode is the process exit code\n200:     ExitCode int\n201:     \n202:     // Stdout is the captured standard output\n203:     Stdout []byte\n204:     \n205:     // Stderr is the captured standard error\n206:     Stderr []byte\n207:     \n208:     // Duration is the execution duration\n209:     Duration time.Duration\n210:     \n211:     // OOMKilled indicates if the process was killed due to OOM\n212:     OOMKilled bool\n213:     \n214:     // Timeout indicates if the command timed out\n215:     Timeout bool\n216: }\n217: \n218: // Run executes a command and waits for completion\n219: func (p *PicoD) Run(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*CommandResult, error)\n220: \n221: // Start starts a command without waiting\n222: func (p *PicoD) Start(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*Process, error)\n223: \n224: // Process represents a running process\n225: type Process struct {\n226:     // PID is the process ID\n227:     PID int\n228:     \n229:     // Wait waits for the process to complete\n230:     Wait() (*CommandResult, error)\n231:     \n232:     // Kill sends a signal to the process\n233:     Kill(signal os.Signal) error\n234: }\n235: ```\n236: \n237: ### 5. Output Streaming (`output.go`)\n238: \n239: ```go\n240: // OutputHandler handles streaming output\n241: type OutputHandler interface {\n242:     // OnStdout is called when stdout data is available\n243:     OnStdout(data []byte)\n244:     \n245:     // OnStderr is called when stderr data is available\n246:     OnStderr(data []byte)\n247:     \n248:     // OnComplete is called when execution completes\n249:     OnComplete(result *CommandResult)\n250: }\n251: \n252: // RunWithStreaming executes a command with streaming output\n253: func (p *PicoD) RunWithStreaming(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command, handler OutputHandler) (*CommandResult, error)\n254: ```\n255: \n256: ### 6. Security Validation (`security.go`)\n257: \n258: ```go\n259: // ValidateCommand validates a command for security\n260: func ValidateCommand(cmd *Command, opts *SecurityOptions) error\n261: \n262: // IsPathSafe checks if a path is within the allowed workspace\n263: func IsPathSafe(path, workDir string) bool\n264: \n265: // DropPrivileges drops privileges to the specified UID/GID\n266: func DropPrivileges(uid, gid int) error\n267: \n268: // SetResourceLimits applies resource limits to the current process\n269: func SetResourceLimits(limits *ResourceLimits) error\n270: ```\n271: \n272: ### 7. Configuration\n273: \n274: #### Environment Variables\n275: \n276: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n277: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n278: | `PICOD_WORKDIR` | No | `/tmp/picod` | Base working directory |\n279: | `PICOD_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT` | No | `30s` | Default command timeout |\n280: | `PICOD_MAX_MEMORY` | No | `128Mi` | Default memory limit |\n281: | `PICOD_MAX_CPU` | No | `1.0` | Default CPU limit |\n282: | `PICOD_MAX_OUTPUT_SIZE` | No | `10MB` | Default output size limit |\n283: | `PICOD_MAX_PROCESSES` | No | `10` | Default process limit |\n284: \n285: ### 8. Error Handling\n286: \n287: ```go\n288: // ExecutionError represents an execution error\n289: type ExecutionError struct {\n290:     // Type is the error type\n291:     Type ExecutionErrorType\n292:     \n293:     // Message is the error message\n294:     Message string\n295:     \n296:     // Underlying is the underlying error\n297:     Underlying error\n298: }\n299: \n300: type ExecutionErrorType string\n301: \n302: const (\n303:     ExecutionErrorTimeout    ExecutionErrorType = \"timeout\"\n304:     ExecutionErrorOOM        ExecutionErrorType = \"oom\"\n305:     ExecutionErrorCancelled  ExecutionErrorType = \"cancelled\"\n306:     ExecutionErrorSecurity   ExecutionErrorType = \"security\"\n307:     ExecutionErrorResource   ExecutionErrorType = \"resource\"\n308:     ExecutionErrorExec       ExecutionErrorType = \"exec\"\n309: )\n310: ```\n311: \n312: ## Impact Analysis\n313: \n314: ### Dependencies\n315: \n316: | Package | Purpose |\n317: |---------|---------|\n318: | `context` | Command cancellation and timeouts |\n319: | `os/exec` | Command execution primitives |\n320: | `syscall` | Process management and signals |\n321: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n322: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | SandboxInfo type definitions |\n323: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1` | Type definitions |\n324: \n325: ### Affected Components\n326: \n327: 1. **Sandbox Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox/`): Will use PicoD for command execution within sandboxes\n328: 2. **Workload Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/`): Will invoke PicoD APIs for job execution\n329: 3. **Code Interpreter** (standalone daemon): Will use PicoD execution logic\n330: 4. **Security Module**: Will configure security policies for command execution\n331: 5. **Monitoring System**: Will collect metrics from command execution\n332: \n333: ### Backward Compatibility\n334: \n335: - This is a new module with no existing API surface\n336: - No breaking changes to existing components\n337: - Configuration via environment variables and programmatic API\n338: - Existing `CodeInterpreter` CRD already references PicoD image\n339: \n340: ### Risk Assessment\n341: \n342: | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n343: |------|------------|--------|------------|\n344: | Command injection | Low | High | Input validation, allowlist-based command selection |\n345: | Resource exhaustion | Medium | High | Enforce strict CPU/memory/time limits |\n346: | Privilege escalation | Low | Critical | Run as non-root, drop capabilities, use namespaces |\n347: | Output buffer overflow | Low | Medium | Stream large outputs, enforce size limits |\n348: | Zombie processes | Medium | Low | Proper process reaping, signal handling |\n349: \n350: ## Alternatives Considered\n351: \n352: ### Alternative 1: Use Existing Library (e.g., go-execute, bazel-remote)\n353: \n354: **Approach**: Leverage existing command execution libraries\n355: \n356: **Pros**:\n357: - Less code to maintain\n358: - Battle-tested implementations\n359: - Community support\n360: \n361: **Cons**:\n362: - May not meet specific security requirements for sandboxed execution\n363: - Additional dependency management overhead\n364: - Less control over resource limit enforcement\n365: - May not support Kubernetes-native patterns\n366: \n367: **Decision**: Implement custom solution for full control over security and limits, and better integration with AgentCube architecture.\n368: \n369: ### Alternative 2: Shell-based Execution\n370: \n371: **Approach**: Execute commands via `/bin/sh -c`\n372: \n373: **Pros**:\n374: - Simple implementation\n375: - Shell features (pipes, redirection) available\n376: - Familiar syntax\n377: \n378: **Cons**:\n379: - Security risks (shell injection attacks)\n380: - Harder to control resource limits accurately\n381: - Additional attack surface\n382: - Non-deterministic behavior across shells\n383: \n384: **Decision**: Use direct execve-style execution for better security and control.\n385: \n386: ### Alternative 3: Container-based Execution\n387: \n388: **Approach**: Spawn a new container for each command\n389: \n390: **Pros**:\n391: - Strong isolation\n392: - Built-in resource limits via cgroups\n393: - Clean environment per command\n394: \n395: **Cons**:\n396: - High overhead (container startup latency)\n397: - Requires container runtime access\n398: - Complex orchestration\n399: - Overkill for simple command execution\n400: \n401: **Decision**: Use process-level isolation with proper limits for lower latency; container isolation is handled at the sandbox pod level (AR-005).\n402: \n403: ## Testing Strategy\n404: \n405: ### Unit Tests\n406: \n407: 1. **TestPicoD_Run_Success**: Basic command execution\n408: 2. **TestPicoD_Run_Timeout**: Command exceeds timeout\n409: 3. **TestPicoD_Run_OOM**: Command exceeds memory limit\n410: 4. **TestPicoD_Run_Cancelled**: Context cancellation\n411: 5. **TestPicoD_OutputCapture**: Stdout/stderr capture\n412: 6. **TestPicoD_SecurityValidation**: Invalid commands rejected\n413: 7. **TestPicoD_ResourceLimits_Validate**: Resource limit validation\n414: 8. **TestPicoD_SecurityOpts_Validate**: Security options validation\n415: 9. **TestPicoD_WithOptions**: Functional options pattern\n416: 10. **TestPicoD_ExecutionErrorTypes**: Error type classification\n417: \n418: ### Integration Tests\n419: \n420: 1. **TestPicoD_Integration_FullLifecycle**: Full execution flow\n421: 2. **TestPicoD_Integration_Concurrent**: Multiple concurrent commands\n422: 3. **TestPicoD_Integration_ResourceLimits**: Verify limits are enforced\n423: 4. **TestPicoD_Integration_Streaming**: Output streaming functionality\n424: 5. **TestPicoD_Integration_SignalHandling**: Process signal handling\n425: \n426: ## Acceptance Criteria\n427: \n428: - [ ] `PicoD` struct implements all required methods\n429: - [ ] Resource limits are enforced (timeout, CPU, memory, output size)\n430: - [ ] Output capture works correctly (stdout, stderr, exit code)\n431: - [ ] Cancellation via context is supported\n432: - [ ] Security validations prevent dangerous operations\n433: - [ ] Streaming output is supported\n434: - [ ] All unit tests pass\n435: - [ ] Integration tests pass\n436: - [ ] Code coverage >= 80%\n437: - [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n438: - [ ] Error types are properly classified and documented\n439: \n440: ## References\n441: \n442: - Sandbox Infrastructure: `changes/AR-012/proposal.md`\n443: - Session Storage: `changes/AR-013/proposal.md`\n444: - Valkey Storage: `changes/AR-014/proposal.md`\n445: - PicoD Spec: `code-execution/spec.md`\n446: - PicoD Design: `code-execution/design.md`\n447: - Client-Go: `deployment/client-go.md`\n\n(End of file - total 447 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal implements the PicoD command execution API for the `pkg/picod` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n\n1. **Secure Command Execution** - Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments with proper isolation\n2. **Resource Limit Enforcement** - Enforce CPU, memory, time, and output size limits on command execution\n3. **Output Capture and Streaming** - Capture stdout/stderr with optional streaming for long-running commands\n4. **Cancellation Support** - Enable command cancellation via context for graceful termination\n5. **Security Hardening** - Implement security validations to prevent privilege escalation and command injection\n\nThis implementation builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in AR-012 and provides the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md","time":{"start":1775863565987,"end":1775863566000}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775863566005,"sessionID":"ses_28648f112ffezeBig0vH7hGGOs","part":{"id":"prt_d79b789f10012JfhEkP4i7fRB7","messageID":"msg_d79b77576001MAkq29V9WgCSOj","sessionID":"ses_28648f112ffezeBig0vH7hGGOs","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_e189a4ef2674417c90f27087","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-011: Router JWT Authentication & Issuance\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: This proposal implements JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication for the `pkg/router` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n6: \n7: 1. **Secure router endpoints** - Require valid JWT tokens for accessing backend services through the router\n8: 2. **Enable stateless authentication** - Use JWT's self-contained nature to avoid server-side session lookups for token validation\n9: 3. **Support token issuance** - Provide endpoints for issuing JWT tokens upon successful authentication\n10: 4. **Integrate with existing session management** - Complement the existing session middleware with JWT-based authentication\n11: \n12: ## Scope\n13: \n14: **Module:** `pkg/router`  \n15: **Language:** Go  \n16: **Size:** M\n17: \n18: This AR covers:\n19: \n20: - **In scope:**\n21:   - JWT validation middleware for router HTTP handlers\n22:   - JWT issuance endpoint for token generation\n23:   - Configuration for JWT secrets and token expiration\n24:   - Integration with existing session management\n25:   - Unit tests for JWT validation and issuance\n26: \n27: - **Out of scope:**\n28:   - User authentication logic (username/password validation)\n29:   - OAuth2/OIDC integration\n30:   - Token refresh mechanisms\n31:   - RBAC/authorization policies (future AR)\n32: \n33: ## Current State Analysis\n34: \n35: ### Existing Authentication Mechanisms\n36: \n37: The current router implementation has session-based authentication:\n38: \n39: 1. **Session Middleware** (`middleware/session_middleware.go`):\n40:    - Extracts session ID from cookies or headers\n41:    - Validates session against session store (memory/Redis)\n42:    - Attaches session to request context\n43:    - `RequireSession` middleware enforces authentication\n44: \n45: 2. **Session Types** (`session/types.go`):\n46:    - `Session` struct with ID, namespace, kind, backend info\n47:    - Session state management (Active, Idle, Expired, Terminated)\n48:    - Configurable expiration and idle timeouts\n49: \n50: 3. **Session Manager** (`session/manager.go`):\n51:    - CRUD operations for sessions\n52:    - Session cleanup and expiration handling\n53: \n54: ### Issues Identified\n55: \n56: 1. **Stateful authentication** - Every request requires a session store lookup\n57: 2. **No token-based auth** - External clients cannot easily authenticate without session cookies\n58: 3. **Limited scalability** - Session store becomes a bottleneck for distributed deployments\n59: 4. **No standard protocol** - Proprietary session mechanism vs. industry-standard JWT\n60: \n61: ### Kubernetes Client-Go Context\n62: \n63: Per `deployment/client-go.md`, the generated client-go library provides:\n64: - Typed clients for `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` resources\n65: - Informers for watching resource changes\n66: - Listers for efficient caching\n67: \n68: **Note:** JWT authentication in the router is orthogonal to Kubernetes RBAC. The router operates at the HTTP layer, while Kubernetes RBAC controls access to the API server.\n69: \n70: ## Proposed Changes\n71: \n72: ### 1. JWT Configuration\n73: \n74: Add JWT configuration to `config.go`:\n75: \n76: ```go\n77: type JWTConfig struct {\n78:     // Enabled enables JWT authentication\n79:     Enabled bool `json:\"enabled\"`\n80:     \n81:     // Secret is the JWT signing secret (HMAC) or path to private key (RSA/ECDSA)\n82:     Secret string `json:\"secret\"`\n83:     \n84:     // SecretPath is the path to the JWT secret file\n85:     SecretPath string `json:\"secretPath\"`\n86:     \n87:     // Algorithm is the signing algorithm (HS256, RS256, ES256)\n88:     Algorithm string `json:\"algorithm\"`\n89:     \n90:     // TokenExpiration is the JWT token expiration duration\n91:     TokenExpiration time.Duration `json:\"tokenExpiration\"`\n92:     \n93:     // Issuer is the JWT issuer claim\n94:     Issuer string `json:\"issuer\"`\n95:     \n96:     // Audience is the expected audience claim\n97:     Audience string `json:\"audience\"`\n98: }\n99: \n100: type RouterConfig struct {\n101:     // ... existing fields ...\n102:     JWT JWTConfig `json:\"jwt\"`\n103: }\n104: ```\n105: \n106: ### 2. JWT Claims Structure\n107: \n108: Define custom claims for AgentCube-specific data:\n109: \n110: ```go\n111: type JWTClaims struct {\n112:     jwt.RegisteredClaims\n113:     \n114:     // UserID is the authenticated user's identifier\n115:     UserID string `json:\"userId\"`\n116:     \n117:     // Namespace is the allowed Kubernetes namespace (optional)\n118:     Namespace string `json:\"namespace,omitempty\"`\n119:     \n120:     // Roles is the list of assigned roles (for future RBAC)\n121:     Roles []string `json:\"roles,omitempty\"`\n122:     \n123:     // SessionID links to an existing session (optional)\n124:     SessionID string `json:\"sessionId,omitempty\"`\n125: }\n126: ```\n127: \n128: ### 3. JWT Middleware\n129: \n130: Create `middleware/jwt_middleware.go`:\n131: \n132: ```go\n133: type JWTMiddleware struct {\n134:     config *JWTConfig\n135:     key    interface{} // Signing key\n136: }\n137: \n138: func (m *JWTMiddleware) Validate(next http.Handler) http.Handler {\n139:     return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n140:         token, err := m.extractToken(r)\n141:         if err != nil {\n142:             m.writeError(w, \"missing token\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n143:             return\n144:         }\n145:         \n146:         claims, err := m.validateToken(token)\n147:         if err != nil {\n148:             m.writeError(w, \"invalid token\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n149:             return\n150:         }\n151:         \n152:         ctx := context.WithValue(r.Context(), JWTClaimsContextKey, claims)\n153:         r = r.WithContext(ctx)\n154:         next.ServeHTTP(w, r)\n155:     })\n156: }\n157: ```\n158: \n159: ### 4. JWT Issuance Endpoint\n160: \n161: Add token issuance handler in `handler.go`:\n162: \n163: ```go\n164: func (h *Handler) IssueToken(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n165:     // Extract credentials from request\n166:     creds, err := h.extractCredentials(r)\n167:     if err != nil {\n168:         h.writeError(w, \"invalid credentials\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n169:         return\n170:     }\n171:     \n172:     // Validate credentials (delegate to auth provider)\n173:     user, err := h.authProvider.Authenticate(r.Context(), creds)\n174:     if err != nil {\n175:         h.writeError(w, \"authentication failed\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n176:         return\n177:     }\n178:     \n179:     // Generate JWT\n180:     token, err := h.jwtSigner.Sign(user)\n181:     if err != nil {\n182:         h.writeError(w, \"token generation failed\", http.StatusInternalServerError)\n183:         return\n184:     }\n185:     \n186:     // Return token\n187:     json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(TokenResponse{\n188:         Token:     token,\n189:         ExpiresIn: h.config.JWT.TokenExpiration.Seconds(),\n190:     })\n191: }\n192: ```\n193: \n194: ### 5. Router Integration\n195: \n196: Update `router.go` to optionally enable JWT middleware:\n197: \n198: ```go\n199: func (r *Router) Start(ctx context.Context) error {\n200:     var handler http.Handler = r.handler\n201:     \n202:     if r.config.JWT.Enabled {\n203:         jwtMiddleware := middleware.NewJWTMiddleware(&r.config.JWT)\n204:         handler = jwtMiddleware.Validate(handler)\n205:     }\n206:     \n207:     server := &http.Server{\n208:         Addr:         r.config.ListenAddr,\n209:         Handler:      handler,\n210:         ReadTimeout:  r.config.ReadTimeout,\n211:         WriteTimeout: r.config.WriteTimeout,\n212:         IdleTimeout:  r.config.IdleTimeout,\n213:     }\n214:     \n215:     // ... rest of startup logic ...\n216: }\n217: ```\n218: \n219: ### 6. Token Issuance Route\n220: \n221: Add dedicated route for token issuance (bypasses JWT validation):\n222: \n223: ```go\n224: func (h *Handler) ServeHTTP(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n225:     // Token issuance endpoint (no auth required)\n226:     if r.Method == http.MethodPost && r.URL.Path == \"/api/v1/auth/token\" {\n227:         h.IssueToken(w, r)\n228:         return\n229:     }\n230:     \n231:     // All other routes require JWT\n232:     route, err := h.resolver.Resolve(r)\n233:     if err != nil {\n234:         h.writeError(w, err, http.StatusNotFound)\n235:         return\n236:     }\n237:     \n238:     if err := h.ProxyRequest(w, r, route); err != nil {\n239:         h.writeError(w, err, http.StatusBadGateway)\n240:     }\n241: }\n242: ```\n243: \n244: ## Impact Analysis\n245: \n246: ### Files to Create\n247: \n248: | File | Purpose |\n249: |------|---------|\n250: | `pkg/router/middleware/jwt_middleware.go` | JWT validation middleware |\n251: | `pkg/router/middleware/jwt_middleware_test.go` | Middleware unit tests |\n252: | `pkg/router/jwt_signer.go` | JWT signing utilities |\n253: | `pkg/router/jwt_signer_test.go` | Signer unit tests |\n254: \n255: ### Files to Modify\n256: \n257: | File | Changes | Impact |\n258: |------|---------|--------|\n259: | `pkg/router/config.go` | Add `JWTConfig` struct | Low - backward compatible |\n260: | `pkg/router/router.go` | Integrate JWT middleware | Medium - affects request flow |\n261: | `pkg/router/handler.go` | Add token issuance endpoint | Medium - new route |\n262: | `pkg/router/types.go` | Add JWT claims context key | Low - additive |\n263: \n264: ### Dependencies\n265: \n266: Add to `go.mod`:\n267: - `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` - JWT parsing and signing\n268: - Optionally: `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5/request` - Token extraction helpers\n269: \n270: ### Backward Compatibility\n271: \n272: - JWT authentication is **disabled by default** (`JWTConfig.Enabled = false`)\n273: - Existing session-based auth continues to work\n274: - Can run both session and JWT middleware in parallel\n275: \n276: ### Testing Impact\n277: \n278: - Unit tests for JWT signing and validation\n279: - Integration tests for token issuance endpoint\n280: - E2E tests for authenticated routing\n281: - Existing tests unaffected (JWT disabled by default)\n282: \n283: ## Alternatives Considered\n284: \n285: ### Alternative 1: Kubernetes ServiceAccount Tokens\n286: \n287: Use Kubernetes ServiceAccount tokens directly.\n288: \n289: **Pros:**\n290: - No additional token management\n291: - Integrates with Kubernetes RBAC\n292: - Standard for in-cluster communication\n293: \n294: **Cons:**\n295: - Tied to Kubernetes cluster\n296: - Requires API server access for validation\n297: - Overkill for simple router auth\n298: - Limited custom claims\n299: \n300: **Decision:** Defer for future Kubernetes-native integration. JWT provides more flexibility.\n301: \n302: ### Alternative 2: mTLS (Mutual TLS)\n303: \n304: Require client certificates for authentication.\n305: \n306: **Pros:**\n307: - Strong authentication\n308: - No token management\n309: - Encrypted by default\n310: \n311: **Cons:**\n312: - Complex certificate management\n313: - Poor UX for external clients\n314: - Harder to debug\n315: - No fine-grained claims\n316: \n317: **Decision:** Too complex for current requirements. Consider for zero-trust deployments.\n318: \n319: ### Alternative 3: Opaque Bearer Tokens\n320: \n321: Use random opaque tokens with server-side storage.\n322: \n323: **Pros:**\n324: - Simple implementation\n325: - Easy to revoke\n326: - No JWT complexity\n327: \n328: **Cons:**\n329: - Requires token store lookup on every request\n330: - Scalability bottleneck\n331: - More infrastructure to maintain\n332: \n333: **Decision:** JWT's stateless validation is preferable for router performance.\n334: \n335: ### Alternative 4: OAuth2/OIDC\n336: \n337: Integrate with full OAuth2/OIDC provider.\n338: \n339: **Pros:**\n340: - Industry standard\n341: - Rich ecosystem\n342: - Built-in user management\n343: \n344: **Cons:**\n345: - Significant implementation complexity\n346: - Requires OAuth2 server\n347: - Overkill for service-to-service auth\n348: \n349: **Decision:** Defer until user authentication requirements mature.\n350: \n351: ## Implementation Checklist\n352: \n353: - [ ] Add `JWTConfig` to `pkg/router/config.go`\n354: - [ ] Create `pkg/router/middleware/jwt_middleware.go`\n355: - [ ] Create `pkg/router/jwt_signer.go`\n356: - [ ] Add token issuance endpoint to `pkg/router/handler.go`\n357: - [ ] Update `pkg/router/router.go` to integrate JWT middleware\n358: - [ ] Write unit tests for JWT validation\n359: - [ ] Write integration tests for token issuance\n360: - [ ] Update documentation in `deployment/`\n361: - [ ] Add example JWT configuration to manifests\n362: \n363: ## Future Considerations\n364: \n365: 1. **Token Refresh** - Implement refresh token mechanism for long-lived sessions\n366: 2. **RBAC Integration** - Use JWT `roles` claim for authorization decisions\n367: 3. **JWKS Support** - Fetch signing keys from JWKS endpoint for multi-tenant setups\n368: 4. **Token Revocation** - Maintain token blacklist for revocation (Redis-backed)\n369: 5. **OAuth2/OIDC** - Integrate with external identity providers\n370: 6. **ServiceAccount Integration** - Accept Kubernetes ServiceAccount tokens\n371: 7. **Audit Logging** - Log JWT claims for audit trails\n372: \n373: ## References\n374: \n375: - [RFC 7519 - JSON Web Token (JWT)](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7519)\n376: - [github.com/golang-jwt/jwt](https://github.com/golang-jwt/jwt)\n377: - [Kubernetes Authentication](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/authentication/)\n378: - Existing session implementation: `pkg/router/session/`\n379: - Session middleware: `pkg/router/middleware/session_middleware.go`\n\n(End of file - total 379 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-011: Router JWT Authentication & Issuance\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal implements JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication for the `pkg/router` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n\n1. **Secure router endpoints** - Require valid JWT tokens for accessing backend services through the router\n2. **Enable stateless authentication** - Use JWT's self-contained nature to avoid server-side session lookups for token validation\n3. **Support token issuance** - Provide endpoints for issuing JWT tokens upon successful authentication\n4. **Integrate with existing session management** - Complement the existing session middleware with JWT-based authentication\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M\n\nThis AR covers:\n\n- **In scope:**","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775863565991,"end":1775863566002}}}}
